int binarySearch(int arr[], int left, int right, int x) {
    while (left <= right) {
        int mid = left + (right - left) / 2;

        // Check if x is present at mid
        if (arr[mid] == x)
            return mid;

        // If x greater, ignore left half
        if (arr[mid] < x)
            left = mid + 1;

        // If x is smaller, ignore right half
        else
            right = mid - 1;
    }

    // if we reach here, then element was not present
    return -1;
}
```

This function takes four arguments: `arr` (the sorted array), `left` (the left index), `right` (the right index), and `x` (the value being searched). It returns the index where `x` is found or `-1` if it's not present in the array. The main idea behind binary search is to repeatedly divide the search interval in half until the target is found or determined not to be present. The algorithm has a time complexity of O(log n) which makes it very efficient compared to linear search (O(n)).

